Participate in our research Join the journey to better health At AgelessRx, we don’t just follow scientific trends—we define them. Every trial, study, and discovery reinforces our mission of advancing longevity science and democratizing access to healthspan-enhancing treatments. Pioneering Innovation Our team of renowned scientists, clinicians, and prescribers use cutting-edge methods and data collection models to shape the future of longevity science. Lab-to-Life Results Our team of renowned scientists, clinicians, and prescribers use science-backed methods to shape the future of longevity science and collect data that empowers your health. Peer-Reviewed Insights Every finding from our research is published in peer-reviewed scientific journals and rigorously analyzed by independent experts to guarantee accuracy, safety, and efficacy. ACTIVE TRIALS Active trials shaping the future of longevity Explore active and ongoing clinical trials designed to uncover the true potential of longevity treatments and personalized longevity solutions for a longer, healthier life. X-Prize Healthspan Initiative Randomized controlled trial evaluating the effectiveness of a targeted, multi-intervention longevity strategy aimed at reversing age-related decline in immune, muscle, and cognitive function. Join us in redefining what’s possible in healthy aging. Microdosing GLP-1s for Longevity Could microdosing GLP-1s make the longevity benefits of Semaglutide more accessible? Our Applied Science team aims to answer this emerging question, exploring whether small doses of GLP-1 could improve pain, brain fog, and symptoms of chronic inflammation. Join trial Life after GLP-1s How can patients best maintain their weight loss benefits once they stop taking GLP-1 medications ? Is it better to slowly wean off, or ease into another weight loss solution? This trial explores potential strategies to help patients sustain their Semaglutide or Tirzepatide benefits for the long term. Join trial Observational Sleep for Longevity An exploration into the efficacy of Trazodone and Tran-Q Sleep on healthy longevity. By evaluating improvements in the quality and quantity of sleep, this trial aims to show how healthy sleep may slow biological aging to improve immunity, cognitive health, and quality of life. Observational GLP-1s for Longevity With help from the AgelessRx GLP-1 community, our Applied Science team aims to demonstrate the longevity benefits of oral and injectable GLP-1s beyond weight loss. Commercial Biobanking for Longevity By contributing blood, plasma, or serum samples, you’ll play a crucial role in shaping the future of personalized longevity treatments to uncover how these interventions impact key aging biomarkers—paving the way for more targeted, science-backed applications in the future. Rapamycin & Oral Health Can Rapamycin slow or even reverse periodontal disease, gum inflammation, or bone loss? The AgelessRx research team investigates the possible benefits of Rapamycin on oral health, based on promising findings from the PEARL trial. Rapamycin & DEXA Scan Using DEXA scans to measure Rapamycin’s efficacy, the research team expands on preliminary findings from the PEARL trial that suggest Rapamycin may improve muscle mass and bone mineral density—all critical for healthy functionality as we age. PAST TRIALS Driving advancements in longevity research Discover the science driving AgelessRx. From clinical research to pioneering new therapies, our past trials have laid the foundation for solutions that have helped hundreds of thousands take charge of their long-term health. PEARL Trial The PEARL Trial is the first large-scale intervention trial on longevity—and one of the first studies to show that low-dose, intermittent Rapamycin is safe for healthy adults. Explore the potential benefits of Rapamycin and read the trial results. Read results Post-COVID Trial A double-blind, placebo-controlled pilot study that shows how LDN and NAD+ improved quality of life and energy for post-COVID patients after 12 weeks, suggesting that the combination of these treatments may be effective in the fight against long COVID. Read results Canagliflozin Study This research trial measured the safety, tolerability, and glucose benefits of Canagliflozin in eliminating excess blood sugar in healthy individuals, opening the door for further studies for enhancing healthy longevity and preventing age-related diseases. Read results Rapamycin Bioavailability Study A cross-sectional study comparing Rapamycin blood levels for compounded versus generic Rapamycin to guide personalized prescription for individual health goals. Discover how the same dose of Rapamycin varies per person, and learn which may be right for you. Read results Acarbose Study Using just a bagel, Acarbose , and a CGM , this trial measured the effects of Acarbose in a healthy individual before and after eating a high-carbohydrate meal, showing that this treatment helps stop glucose spikes in their tracks. Read results Rapamycin & LDN for Bone Mineral Density A clinical case study of a 52-year-old woman taking both Rapamycin and LDN to treat reduced bone miner density (BMD). Discover how this cutting-edge combination therapy emerges as a potential treatment for prevalent bone disorders like osteopenia and osteoporosis. Read results The future of longevity science We’re always looking ahead at the future of longevity research as we continue to push boundaries and redefine possibilities. Check back to explore more cutting-edge developments from our Applied Science team and discover new opportunities to contribute to longevity research. Other publications Our commitment to longevity extends beyond clinical trials. From observational and quality-of-life studies to clinical case studies and retrospective research, explore our additional longevity research efforts. SF-36 Quality of Life Study A review study exploring the value of the SF-36 health survey as a valuable measure of real-world evidence for quality of life metrics. Learn More Low Dose Naltrexone enhances healthspan An observational study assessing the change in healthspan metrics in a real-world cohort of 5500 people, adding to the growing evidence for LDN as a geroprotective medicine. We prioritize transparency, accessibility, and equity for each research participant, ensuring that our efforts benefit everyone—not just a select few. Read more How to Increase Energy Production with Age | AgelessRx Skip to content Search for: Here’s what we’ll cover in this blog post: The connection between energy and aging Why mitochondria are your body’s secret powerhouses How ATP keeps you feeling young and vibrant Easy tips to keep your energy levels high as you age Ever feel like aging is slowly draining your energy? What if you could hang onto that same energy you felt when you were twenty and increase energy production as you age? According to the energy maintenance theory of aging , it’s possible! The key lies in keeping your cells energized, as those who age best have cells that excel at maintaining energy production over time. The driving force behind this energy? Your mitochondria—the powerhouses of our cells . These tiny engines produce ATP—the fuel your body needs to repair, grow, and keep your muscles and brain in top shape. As we age, our mitochondria slow down. Less ATP means less energy, and soon our bodies feel like they’re running on a low battery. This can show up as weaker muscles, brain fog, and a higher chance of illness. The good news? If we keep our mitochondria healthy, we can stay sharp, strong, and energized for years to come. But what exactly happens to our mitochondria as we age, and how does it impact the aging process? Mitochondrial Dysfunction and Aging Mitochondrial dysfunction is one of the hallmarks of aging . As we age, our mitochondria weaken, unlike the pristine powerhouses you’d find in a toddler’s cells. Damaged mitochondria struggle to produce enough energy, leading to fatigue and other signs of aging. When our cells can’t produce the energy they need, everything slows down—immune function, metabolism, and even brain performance. However, improving mitochondrial efficiency can not only help our bodies keep up with life’s demands, but it may even slow down the aging process. Feeling Fatigued? It Might Be a Bigger Deal Everyone gets tired, but chronic fatigue could signal a bigger issue. Fatigue can be an early warning sign of conditions like heart disease, diabetes, or even cancer. What’s going on behind the scenes? It might be a lack of cellular energy with declining ATP production that’s driving that ongoing tiredness. By improving mitochondrial health and working to boost ATP production, you can give your body the energy it needs to fight fatigue and stay resilient against disease as you age. Whether with supplements or lifestyle changes, supporting ATP synthesis can help you feel more energy and even slow down the effects of aging. How Can You Boost Mitochondrial Health? With easy lifestyle changes, you can boost your mitochondrial health and increase energy production: Exercise Regularly : Physical activity generates new mitochondria and strengthens the existing ones. Keep moving with activities like walking, yoga, or weight training. Eat a Balanced Diet : Fuel your cells with antioxidant-rich foods like leafy greens, fish, and nuts. These nutrients support mitochondria and overall health while giving us more energy. Manage Stress : Chronic stress can damage mitochondria. Practice relaxation techniques like meditation, yoga, or deep breathing to keep stress levels in check. Consider Select Treatments and Supplements : NAD+ , B12 , Coenzyme Q10, magnesium, or alpha-lipoic acid can all be beneficial in supporting energy production and mitochondrial health. Recharge Your Batteries with Expert Help Optimizing your energy levels as you age doesn’t have to be a solo mission. Sometimes, we all need a little assistance—especially when it comes to something as important as your long-term health. A longevity specialist (like our team at AgelessRx) can help tailor a plan with the right balance of diet, exercise, and supplements. If you’re looking to increase your mitochondrial health and optimize your energy for years to come, try scheduling a longevity consultation with an AgelessRx prescriber. You can also explore our expert-curated energy and fatigue treatments, like NAD+ or B12 injections, both of which have been shown to potentially help improve energy  for more healthy, life-filled years. LDN 0.5 vs 1.5: What to Know Before You Buy | AgelessRx Skip to content Search for: Quick overview of what we’ll cover in this blog post: What to know before you buy LDN Why AgelessRx offers 2 starting doses The difference between 0.5mg & 1.5mg Who should start at which dose What to do if you want a different dose What to Know Before You Buy LDN Naltrexone is an enigmatic treatment whose benefits vary depending on which dosage you’re receiving. Just by the name alone, we can tell that Low Dose Naltrexone (LDN) is on the lower end of this spectrum, and its ideal use strays significantly from higher doses – namely, in how it affects our longevity. But the name shouldn’t suggest that there’s a single dose of LDN that’s considered the low dose. In fact, anything under 10mg of Naltrexone can be considered LDN. This begs the question: just how low do the doses go, and which dose is right for me? These questions are what drove us at AgelessRx to offer multiple starting doses for LDN. Below, we discuss the differences between these starting doses (0.5mg and 1.5mg), so you can make the most informed decision with your prescriber about what might be best for you. Here’s what to know before you buy LDN. Why the Low Dose? Many medications have different effects (and therefore different uses) when prescribed at higher or lower doses, and LDN is no exception. Naltrexone is most often prescribed to treat certain addictions at doses ranging from 50-150mg. When prescribed at these doses, Naltrexone acts as an antagonist to temporarily block the effects of certain drugs and naturally occurring dopamine, as well as the release of dopamine (the reward signal associated with drug addiction). When used at lower doses, though, Naltrexone appears to have a paradoxical effect that allows the brain to produce more endorphins, which help to improve pain relief. Additionally, lower doses of Naltrexone may also prevent overactivation of immune cells in the body and the brain (known as T-cells and microglia respectively), thereby blunting the destructive consequences of chronic inflammation. For these benefits, Naltrexone is prescribed at 9mg/day or under. The most common dose is usually 4.5mg/day, at which most users experience the greatest benefits with th

What Are SARMS? - We Have SARMS For Sale A Selective androgen receptor modulator (SARM) is a type of drug that is designed to selectively bind to androgen receptors in specific tissues, such as muscle and bone. This means that SARMs can have anabolic effects (building muscle) without the same androgenic effects (masculinizing effects) as testosterone. SARMs were first developed in the early 1990s after Dalton and Miller, who discovered that aryl propionamides with structural similarities to bicalutamide and hydroxyflutamide could activate AR-dependent transcriptional activity provided the early lead for the development of diaryl propionamide class of SARMs. However, SARMs are not currently approved for use in humans, and there is a limited amount of research on their safety and efficacy. The potential benefits of SARMs include their anabolic effects without the same androgenic effects as testosterone. This could make them useful for treating conditions such as muscle wasting and osteoporosis. However, the potential risks of SARMs include liver toxicity, cardiovascular disease, and prostate cancer. Different Types of SARMS The majority of SARMs found in the market can typically be encountered in three distinct variations: Powder SARMS: Initially, all SARMs exist as a powdered substance, which is then transformed into either tablet, encased within capsules, or converted into a liquid form. Every SARM initially starts in a powder state. This is the reason many researchers regard powdered SARMs as the most unadulterated version of these medicinal compounds. Powdered SARMs can be effortlessly portioned into the specific quantity needed by the investigator. Gel SARMS: GEL SARMs enjoy considerable popularity as well. They are also referred to as SARMs Capsules.  The enthusiasm primarily stems from the convenience of not needing to measure out capsules, thus making the process more straightforward for researchers. GEL SARMs maintain their initial purity for extended durations. GEL also safeguards the strength of the encapsulated ingredients. This guarantees the uniformity and effectiveness of each individual dose. Active components in liquids have been observed to diminish in potency over time. Liquid SARMS: Liquid SARMs are recognized for their exceptional purity and extended half-life. When appropriately stored, they possess a lengthy shelf life and can be effortlessly measured and preserved. Liquid SARMs hold a distinctive appeal for researchers due to the ease of measuring precise quantities for administration to subjects, with or without water. They demonstrate potential in their respective research fields for those who find it challenging to utilize capsules or pills, particularly when working with animals. What is a Certificate of Analysis (COA)? A Certificate of Analysis (COA) is a document produced by an independent or in-house analytical laboratory verifying a compound’s identity, purity, and concentration using methods like HPLC, LC-MS, or NMR. What is High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC)? HPLC is a laboratory technique that separates components in a mixture by passing solvent under high pressure through a column to quantify purity or detect contaminants. What is Liquid Chromatography–Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS)? LC-MS combines liquid chromatography with mass spectrometry to separate, identify, and quantify molecular species by mass-to-charge ratio. What does ≥ 99% purity mean? ≥ 99% purity indicates that 99 percent or more of a sample is the target analyte; impurities (≤1%) are the detectable residual substances. What does “Research Use Only” (RUO) mean? Research Use Only (RUO) means the compound is explicitly for laboratory, analytical, or experimental use—not for medical, diagnostic, or human consumption. Focus on Nootropics – Why They Matter in Research Nootropics (also known as “cognitive enhancers”) are molecules studied for their effects on brain function, memory, focus, and neuroprotection.
